# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1985-86-australian-tri-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The **1969–70 Vehicle & General Australasian knock-out competition** was a List A tournament took place from November 1969 to January 1970.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] It was the first season of the Australian domestic limited-overs cricket tournament.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Seven teams representing the six states in Australia, and a New Zealand team, took part in the competition in a knockout format.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The competition began on 22 November 1969 when Victoria took on Tasmania at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] After five matches were played, the final took place on 1 January 1970 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground between Victoria and New Zealand.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] After winning the toss, Victoria were bowled out for 129, with New Zealand chasing the total down with six wickets to spare.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The first season of the competition was a straight knockout competition between the six states of Australia and a team that represented New Zealand at domestic level.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The **1970–71 Vehicle & General Australasian knock-out competition** was the second edition of the official List A domestic tournament in Australia.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Seven teams representing six states in Australia and New Zealand took part in the knock-out competition.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The competition began on 18 October 1970 when South Australia took on Victoria at the Adelaide Oval.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The 1970–71 cup final was played on 6 February 1971 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground between Queensland and Western Australia, with Western Australia recording an 91 run victory over Queensland.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Ian Chappell scored the most runs in the tournament with 176 runs with Graham McKenzie from Western Australia taking the most wickets with eight.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The second season of the competition was a straight knockout competition between the six states of Australia and a team that represented New Zealand at the domestic level.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The **Benson & Hedges World Series Cup** was a cricket tournament held in Australia from 27 November 1979 to 22 January 1980.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] It was a tri-nations series featuring Australia, England and the West Indies, with all of the matches being played as One Day Internationals (ODI).
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The series was part of the English and West Indian tour and was the first official tri-nations series after World Series Cricket.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] After the round-robin matches which were played at four venues in Adelaide, Brisbane, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] England and the West Indies reached the final where the West Indies won the final series 2–0.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The red ball was used and the white pads were worn for the matches in Adelaide, Brisbane and Melbourne, and the white ball was used and the coloured pads were worn for the matches in Sydney.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] England and West Indies would not contest the tri-series again until the 1986-87 season.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1980-81-australia-tri-nation-series] The **1980–81 Australia Tri-Nation Series** (more commonly known as the **1980–81 World Series**) was a cricket tournament held in Australia from 23 November 1980 to 3 February 1981.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1980-81-australia-tri-nation-series] It was the second edition of the Australian Tri-Series, with Australia playing host to India and New Zealand.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1980-81-australia-tri-nation-series] The series was a part of the Indian and New Zealand tours.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1980-81-australia-tri-nation-series] After matches were played in Adelaide, Brisbane, Melbourne, Sydney and Perth throughout the entire group-stage, Australia and New Zealand qualified for the finals where after the underarm incident in the third final, Australia went on to win 3–1.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1981-82-australia-tri-nation-series] The **1981–82 World Series** was a One Day International (ODI) cricket tri-series where Australia played host to Pakistan and West Indies.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1981-82-australia-tri-nation-series] Australia and West Indies reached the Finals, with West Indies winning the best-of-five final series 3–1.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1981-82-australia-tri-nation-series] West Indies won the best of five final series against Australia 3–1.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1982-83-australian-tri-series] The **1982–83 Benson & Hedges World Series Cup** was a One Day International (ODI) cricket tri-series where Australia played host to England and New Zealand.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1982-83-australian-tri-series] Australia and New Zealand reached the Finals, which Australia won 2–0.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1982-83-australian-tri-series] Australia won the best of three final series against New Zealand 2–0.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1983-84-australian-tri-series] The **1983–84 World Series** was a One Day International (ODI) cricket tri-series where Australia played host to Pakistan and West Indies.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1983-84-australian-tri-series] Australia and West Indies reached the Finals, which West Indies won 2–0.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1983-84-australian-tri-series] West Indies won the best of three final series against Australia 2–0.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1985-86-australian-tri-series] The **1985–86 Benson & Hedges World Series** was a One Day International (ODI) cricket tri-series where Australia played host to India and New Zealand.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1985-86-australian-tri-series] Australia and India reached the Finals, which Australia won 2–0.
[src:1985-86-australian-tri-series/1985-86-australian-tri-series] Australia won the best of three final series against India 2–0.
